node.text:
Earlier this year, the EU approved the sale of the first total artificial heart (TAH) for patients that desperately require a working heart while they wait for a live donor. 

Now, a team from Duke University has performed the first transplant of this artificial heart in the US, potentially saving the life of a 39-year-old man with sudden heart failure. The heart should allow Matthew Moore to stabilize and even return home, if all goes well, while he waits for a full transplant.
​
​The full story can be found by hitting this image via the link in our bio. 📖

Check out the unbelievably cute Bargibanti pygmy seahorse! These little pink critters are tiny, usually growing to less than 2cm (0.79 in). As if their size doesn’t make them difficult enough to spot, their clever camouflage makes them even trickier to find in the wild. They can spend their entire life on a single gorgonian coral by wrapping their tail around them and anchoring them in place, relying on water currents to bring them very small particles of food. So little is actually known about this seahorse that scientists and conservationists don’t even know if the species is under threat!
​

node.text:
This shiny critter is the Jewel Wasp, or Emerald Cockroach Wasp (Ampulex compressa). It looks absolutely stunning, and it’ll make you even more glad than you already are that you aren’t a cockroach. It’s a parasitoid wasp that uses cockroaches as a live food supply for its developing larva, and it manages to coax this poor unsuspecting bug into playing host in a horrifying way.

The jewel wasp starts off the attack by stinging the cockroach around the midsection, paralyzing the front legs. Now that the cockroach is practically immobilized, the wasp goes for a second, more precise sting into the head, injecting venom directly into the victim’s brain. While several mind-manipulating organisms exist, the jewel wasp is the only known parasite that injects venom directly into the brain of a host. The venom blocks a particular neurotransmitter called octopamine which controls its motivation to walk. Although the cockroach is not entirely paralyzed, it loses the will to escape and is effectively turned into a zombie nursery.

The wasp then drags the enslaved cockroach into its underground lair and lays an egg into the roach’s abdomen. The egg hatches, and the young eats the host’s insides while it is still alive (they rot quickly when dead, and no one wants to eat rotting insides). The cockroach dies about 8 days later, inside which the larva forms a snug cocoon, ready to emerge around a month later. Yikes.
​
​Image credit: Glass and Nature / Shutterstock, yod67 / Shutterstock.

Happy #UnderwaterWednesday! Feather stars are an ancient species of marine invertebrate belonging to the class Crinoidea, and are usually red and white in color. It uses its many arms which have feathery fringes to swim, and its finger-like cirri to cling to its perch and crawl along the seabed snacking on plankton and other food in its way.

Feather stars inhabit many infestors that feed on its waste such as clingfish which wiggle their way around the arms. Talk about skimping out on rent!

node.text:
As reported in the International Journal of Dream Research, a team from the Phase Research Center in Russia suggests that some alien abduction stories may simply be explained by dreaming during REM sleep

For their study, the researchers gathered 152 people who claimed to have previously experienced a lucid dream – a type of dream where the dreamer becomes aware that they are dreaming – and asked them to attempt to “try to find or summon aliens or UFOs” during their usual night's sleep at home. They found that 114 of the volunteers (75 percent) were able to successfully experience a dream that featured extraterrestrials or some kind of alien abduction.

Out of the people who successfully dreamed of aliens, 61 percent said the alien characters resembled extraterrestrials from sci-fi movies and novels, while 19 percent met aliens that looked like “ordinary people" and 4 percent said they were invisible.
​
​Read the full story by hitting this image post via the link in our bio. 👽

node.text:
The Hubble Space Telescope has all its scientific instruments back online. Following a worrying month trying to get the veteran observatory to work again, NASA approved a daring approach last week. Over the course of several days, the solution worked, and the ground team was able to slowly get the telescope completely back online.  
​
​“Hubble is an icon, giving us incredible insight into the cosmos over the past three decades,” NASA Administrator Bill Nelson said in a statement. “I’m proud of the Hubble team, from current members to Hubble alumni who stepped in to lend their support and expertise. Thanks to their dedication and thoughtful work, Hubble will continue to build on its 31-year legacy, broadening our horizons with its view of the universe.”
​
​Credit: NASA

No, it’s not a UFO – but it does look like one! This was the test flight of ‘Avrocar’ – a secret US Airforce hovercraft project developed in the 1950s during the early years of the Cold War.
​
With a diameter of 18ft (5.5 meters) and weight of over 3,000 lbs (1,361 kg), it was hoped the flying-saucer-shaped craft could travel at speeds of hundreds of miles per hour at high altitudes, though it managed neither. The underside of the vehicle featured a massive ‘turborotor’, effectively a giant fan powered by three jet engines, which aimed at the ground and kept it hovering in the air.
​
The US Army had hoped to develop it into a combat-ready helicopter, however the technology proved too problematic. The angular momentum generated by the turborotor was intended to act like a gyroscope, however, during test flights such as in this video, the vehicle had too many issues remaining stable.
​
In December 1961, funding for the project ran out, and the Avrocar project was cancelled.
​ 
Credit: Public Domain / IFLScience

node.text:
Aside from being extremely cute, the Thorny Devil lizard has some pretty cool traits!
​
Commonly found in the arid scrubland and desert of Central and Western Australia, these lizards have an unusual way of walking involving frequent pauses, which is thought to help them stay hidden from predators. Thorny Devils even have some strange dining habits. Their mouths have evolved specifically to feed only on small ants, and because of this, they are incapable of drinking the way most other animals do.
​
Instead, these lizards will bury themselves in damp sand where they use special capillary channels to absorb moisture, and that water is then drawn up into its mouth. They can also collect water from wet sand by shoveling it onto their backs!
​
